<doc id="905850" wikidata="Q3075270" url="?curid=905850" title="Supermodular function">
<text>In mathematics, a supermodular function is a function on a lattice that, informally, has the property of being characterized by &quot;increasing differences.&quot; Seen from the point of set functions, this can also be viewed as a relationship of &quot;increasing returns&quot;, where adding more elements to a subset increases its valuation. In economics, supermodular functions are often used as a formal expression of complementarity in preferences among goods. Supermodular functions are studied and have applications in game theory, economics, lattice theory, combinatorial optimization, and machine learning.

== Definition ==
Let formula_1 be a lattice. A real-valued function formula_2 is called supermodular if 
formula_3

for all formula_4. 

If the inequality is strict, then formula_5 is strictly supermodular on formula_6. If formula_7 is (strictly) supermodular then &quot;f&quot; is called (strictly) submodular. A function that is both submodular and supermodular is called modular. This corresponds to the inequality being changed to an equality.

We can also define supermodular functions where the underlying lattice is the vector space formula_8. Then the function formula_9 is supermodular if 

formula_10

for all formula_11, formula_12, where formula_13 denotes the componentwise maximum and formula_14 the componentwise minimum of formula_11 and formula_16.

If &quot;f&quot; is twice continuously differentiable, then supermodularity is equivalent to the condition

:formula_17

==Supermodularity in economics and game theory==
The concept of supermodularity is used in the social sciences to analyze how one agent&#x27;s decision affects the incentives of others.

Consider a symmetric game with a smooth payoff function formula_18 defined over actions formula_19 of two or more players formula_20. Suppose the action space is continuous; for simplicity, suppose each action is chosen from an interval: formula_21. In this context, supermodularity of formula_18 implies that an increase in player formula_23&#x27;s choice formula_19 increases the marginal payoff formula_25 of action formula_26 for all other players formula_27. That is, if any player formula_23 chooses a higher formula_19, all other players formula_27 have an incentive to raise their choices formula_26 too. Following the terminology of Bulow, Geanakoplos, and Klemperer (1985), economists call this situation strategic complementarity, because players&#x27; strategies are complements to each other. This is the basic property underlying examples of multiple equilibria in coordination games.

The opposite case of supermodularity of formula_18, called submodularity, corresponds to the situation of strategic substitutability. An increase in formula_19 lowers the marginal payoff to all other player&#x27;s choices formula_26, so strategies are substitutes. That is, if formula_23 chooses a higher formula_19, other players have an incentive to pick a &quot;lower&quot; formula_26.

For example, Bulow et al. consider the interactions of many imperfectly competitive firms. When an increase in output by one firm raises the marginal revenues of the other firms, production decisions are strategic complements. When an increase in output by one firm lowers the marginal revenues of the other firms, production decisions are strategic substitutes.

A supermodular utility function is often related to complementary goods. However, this view is disputed.

==Supermodular set functions==
Supermodularity can also be defined for set functions, which are functions defined over subsets of a larger set. Many properties of submodular set functions can be rephrased to apply to supermodular set functions.

Intuitively, a supermodular function over a set of subsets demonstrates &quot;increasing returns&quot;. This means that if each subset is assigned a real number that corresponds to its value, the value of a subset will always be less than the value of a larger subset which contains it. Alternatively, this means that as we add elements to a set, we increase its value.

=== Definition ===
Let formula_38 be a finite set. A set function formula_39 is supermodular if it satifies the following (equivalent) conditions:

# formula_40 for all formula_41.
# formula_42 for all formula_43, where formula_44.

A set function formula_5 is submodular if formula_7 is supermodular, and modular if it is both supermodular and submodular.

=== Additional Facts ===

* If formula_47 is modular and formula_48 is submodular, then formula_49 is a supermodular function.
* A non-negative supermodular function is also a superadditive function.

== Optimization Techniques ==
There are specialized techniques for optimizing submodular functions. Theory and enumeration algorithms for finding local and global maxima (minima) of submodular (supermodular) functions can be found in &quot;Maximization of submodular functions: Theory and enumeration algorithms&quot;, B. Goldengorin.

